etymologies: early 17th century (in nautical use in the sense ‘a circle of rope used as a fastening’): from obsolete French grommette, from gourmer ‘to curb’, of unknown ultimate origin. Current senses date from the mid 20th century

definitions: an eyelet placed in a hole in a sheet or panel to protect or insulate a rope or cable passed through it or to prevent the sheet or panel from being torn.
shortDefinitions: eyelet placed in hole to protect or insulate rope or cable passed through it

definitions: a tube surgically implanted in the eardrum to drain fluid from the middle ear.
shortDefinitions: tube surgically implanted in eardrum to drain fluid from middle ear

definitions: a young or inexperienced skier, snowboarder, surfer, or skateboarder

examples.text: mega moves that make gods out of grommets

shortDefinitions: young or inexperienced surfer or skateboarder
